1. Inputs
Feature collections (per lottery, e.g. Euromillones):
    *_feature (euromillones_feature, la_primitiva_feature, el_gordo_feature)
    Fields: main_number, stars/clave/C/R, frequency, gap, etc.
Model layer (what you’ll train / already have):
    Frequency / gap / hot models (existing backend).
    New ML models (LSTM/RNN, RF/GBM, etc.) you will add on top.
2. Build a per‑number prediction model (from feature collection)
    For each lottery (start with Euromillones):

    -Create training dataset from *_feature:
        For draw (t) (row (t) in euromillones_feature):
            Features X_t:
            e.g. frequency, gap, main_dx, star_dx, hot/cold flags, weekday…
        Labels y_{t+1}:
        one‑hot vectors saying which numbers appear in draw (t+1) (mains 1–50, stars 1–12).
    -Train per‑number models:
        For mains: X_t → P(main n in next draw) for all (n=1..50).
        For stars: X_t → P(star s in next draw) for (s=1..12).
        Models:
            Start with RF/GBM or simple NN.
            Later add LSTM/RNN (sequence of X_t over time) and ensemble them.
    -Save the trained models (e.g. joblib or Torch) and version them.

3. Generate per‑number probabilities for next draw
At prediction time:

    -Take the latest row from *_feature (last draw).
    -Build its feature vector X_T.
    -Run through the model(s) to get:
    (p^\text{main}_n = P(\text{main}=n)) for all mains.
    (p^\text{star}_s = P(\text{star}=s)) for all stars (or C/R/clave, for other lotteries).
    Optionally ensemble existing frequency/gap/hot models:
    (p^\text{final} = w_1 p^\text{ML} + w_2 p^\text{freq} + w_3 p^\text{gap} + …)
    This gives you a probability vector per position.

4. Build a high‑probability number pool
Using the probabilities:
    Rank numbers:
        Sort mains by (p^\text{final}_n), stars (or C/R) by their probabilities.
        Choose pool sizes:
            Example (Euromillones):
                Main pool: top K_main (e.g. 20–30) mains.
                Star pool: top K_star (e.g. 6–8) stars.
        Apply neuro‑symbolic / rule filters (optional):
            Drop numbers that violate rules (e.g. too many consecutive, sum out of band).
            Or just keep a “soft” score for these constraints for later.
    Result: number pool P_main, P_star (and P_C, P_R for La Primitiva / P_clave for El Gordo).

5. Produce a candidate ticket pool (~3000 tickets)
Now you go from number pools to tickets:

    Initial random tickets:
        Sample many tickets using probabilities:
            For each ticket:
                Sample 5 (or 6) mains from P_main (weighted by prob, without replacement).
            Sample stars/C/R/clave from their pools.
    Generate more than 3000 (e.g. 10k) to have material for selection.
Evaluate tickets (Monte Carlo):
    For each ticket:
        Approximate its quality:
            Expected matches w.r.t. the probability model.
            Or simulate many possible next draws from the model (Monte Carlo) and compute average prize/hits.
    This uses Monte Carlo simulations (requirement 8).
(Optional) Genetic algorithm refinement:
    Treat each ticket (or set of tickets) as a chromosome.
    Fitness = Monte‑Carlo score (expected hits/return).
    Run GA:
        Selection → better tickets.
        Crossover → mix parts of good tickets.
        Mutation → tweak numbers randomly.
    After N generations, keep the best ~3000 tickets.
Rule‑based post‑filtering (neuro‑symbolic):
    Apply hard rules (no all‑even, limit high/low, no extreme sums).
    This is where neuro‑symbolic ideas come in: models + domain rules.
Result: a ticket pool of ~3000 “best” tickets.

6. Expose to the app
Backend API:
    Add e.g. GET /api/euromillones/prediction/tickets:
        Runs step 3–5 (or uses precomputed results in Mongo).
        Returns:
            per‑number probabilities,
            ticket pool (list of tickets with scores).
Frontend:
    In the Euromillones Predicción page, add:
        Probability charts (bars by number).
        Ticket pool table/grid (top N tickets, with score, filters, etc.).
7. Summary pipeline
Feature collection (*_feature) → training dataset.
Train per‑number models (NN/RF/LSTM) → save models.
Latest feature row → per‑number probabilities.
Probabilities → number pool (mains + stars/C/R/clave).
Number pool + Monte Carlo + GA + rules → ~3000‑ticket pool.
Ticket pool → backend API → Predicción UI.